00:02:15.860 --> 00:02:18.503
And now, a few words about Carol Greider.

00:02:20.540 --> 00:02:24.260
Carol Greider is internationally renowned

00:02:24.260 --> 00:02:25.830
for her important contributions

00:02:25.830 --> 00:02:28.320
to the field of molecular biology.

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:31.680
She was awarded the 2009 Nobel Prize

00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:33.690
for physiology of medicine,

00:02:33.690 --> 00:02:37.080
along with Elizabeth
Blackburn and Jack Szostak,

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:39.280
for their discovery that genetic sequences

00:02:39.280 --> 00:02:41.540
known as telomeres are protected

00:02:41.540 --> 00:02:45.210
from progressive shortening
by the enzyme telomerase.

00:02:45.210 --> 00:02:48.890
Greider discovered telomerase in 1984,

00:02:48.890 --> 00:02:50.690
while working with Elizabeth Bradford

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:52.963
at the University of California Berkeley.

00:02:54.958 --> 00:02:56.150
Telomeres are essential

00:02:56.150 --> 00:02:58.750
to chromosome maintenance and stability.

00:02:58.750 --> 00:03:01.160
In the absence of telomerase,

00:03:01.160 --> 00:03:04.250
telomeres shorten
progressively as cells divide,

00:03:04.250 --> 00:03:06.160
eventually leading to cell death

00:03:07.380 --> 00:03:10.330
or cellular senescence.

00:03:10.330 --> 00:03:13.840
Greider's understanding,
Greider's breakthrough discovery

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:16.210
of telomerase enzyme that allowed

00:03:16.210 --> 00:03:19.460
a mechanistic understanding
of cellular reproduction,

00:03:19.460 --> 00:03:22.190
opening new avenues of
research into cancer

00:03:22.190 --> 00:03:24.610
and age-related diseases.

00:03:24.610 --> 00:03:27.360
Greider received her BA in biology

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:29.010
from the University of California,

00:03:29.010 --> 00:03:33.980
Santa Barbara, in 1983, her
PhD in molecular biology

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:36.570
at the University of
California, Berkeley, in 1987.

00:03:37.690 --> 00:03:39.700
She was a Cold Spring Harbor fellow

00:03:39.700 --> 00:03:41.880
and later held a faculty position

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:43.780
at the Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:45.540
in Long Island, New York.

00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:47.980
In 1997, she joined the faculty

00:03:47.980 --> 00:03:50.900
of the Department of
Molecular Biology and Genetics

00:03:50.900 --> 00:03:52.790
at Johns Hopkins University

00:03:52.790 --> 00:03:55.900
where she is currently the
Daniel Nathans professor

00:03:55.900 --> 00:03:58.830
and director of molecular
biology and genetics,

00:03:58.830 --> 00:04:00.920
as well as professor of oncology

00:04:00.920 --> 00:04:04.900
in the John Hopkins
University School of Medicine.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:07.520
Greider also directs her
own research laboratory

00:04:07.520 --> 00:04:09.930
at the University which conducts research

00:04:09.930 --> 00:04:12.900
into telomere function and structure.

00:04:12.900 --> 00:04:15.580
In recognition of her
groundbreaking research,

00:04:15.580 --> 00:04:17.020
Greider has been named a fellow

00:04:17.020 --> 00:04:20.040
by the American Academy of Microbiology,

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:23.310
the American Association for
the Advancement of Science,

00:04:23.310 --> 00:04:25.960
the American Academy of Arts and Sciences,

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:29.190
and as a member of the
National Academy of Sciences

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:31.440
and the Institute of Medicine.

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:34.270
In addition to her Nobel Prize
for physiology of medicine,

00:04:34.270 --> 00:04:37.090
she has received a number of other awards

00:04:37.090 --> 00:04:38.410
in the last 10 years,

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:41.980
including the Pearl
Meister Greengard Prize,

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:45.340
the Paul Ehrlich, Ludwig
Darmstaedter Prize,

00:04:45.340 --> 00:04:47.550
the Kathryn Burke and Judd Award,

00:04:47.550 --> 00:04:51.560
the Richard Lounsbery Award,
the Dickson Prize in Medicine,

00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:54.170
the Wiley Prize in Biomedical Sciences

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:56.630
and the Louisa Gross Horowitz Prize.

00:04:56.630 --> 00:04:58.270
An amazing list.

00:04:58.270 --> 00:04:59.700
Greider has also published

00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:02.050
over 100 articles and book chapters.

